00:00:11.477 --> 00:00:24.779 align:middle line:90%


00:00:24.779 --> 00:00:26.570 align:middle line:10%
>>GEORGE NOORY: Welcome
to "Beyond Belief."

00:00:26.570 --> 00:00:28.460 align:middle line:10%
I'm George Noory with
our special guest,

00:00:28.460 --> 00:00:31.520 align:middle line:10%
Michael Jaye, a former
army officer who

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:32.870 align:middle line:10%
taught at West Point.

00:00:32.870 --> 00:00:35.450 align:middle line:10%
He taught mathematics
and has written a book

00:00:35.450 --> 00:00:37.400 align:middle line:10%
called "The Worldwide Flood."

00:00:37.400 --> 00:00:39.650 align:middle line:84%
How did you get
involved in studying

00:00:39.650 --> 00:00:43.649 align:middle line:84%
the worldwide flood, which
happened 12,000 some years ago?

00:00:43.649 --> 00:00:44.690 align:middle line:90%
>>MICHAEL JAYE: Yes, sir.

00:00:44.690 --> 00:00:48.230 align:middle line:10%
So I just retired
from West Point,

00:00:48.230 --> 00:00:51.372 align:middle line:10%
and we moved out to
Monterey, California.

00:00:51.372 --> 00:00:52.400 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: California.

00:00:52.400 --> 00:00:56.300 align:middle line:10%
>>JAYE: And someone
who had known me

00:00:56.300 --> 00:00:58.070 align:middle line:10%
from my undergraduate
days suggested

00:00:58.070 --> 00:01:01.550 align:middle line:10%
that I take a look at Monterey
Canyon right off the coast.

00:01:01.550 --> 00:01:04.250 align:middle line:84%
Now we moved there
just about the time

00:01:04.250 --> 00:01:06.860 align:middle line:84%
when Google was making
its maps available to us.

00:01:06.860 --> 00:01:07.680 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: OK.

00:01:07.680 --> 00:01:10.580 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: And so I
turned on Google Maps.

00:01:10.580 --> 00:01:13.970 align:middle line:84%
And I looked at this
image of Monterey Canyon.

00:01:13.970 --> 00:01:17.700 align:middle line:90%
And what I saw raised--

00:01:17.700 --> 00:01:19.309 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Red flags?

00:01:19.309 --> 00:01:20.850 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: --some
interesting questions.

00:01:20.850 --> 00:01:24.660 align:middle line:10%
First, there are
submerged rivers

00:01:24.660 --> 00:01:26.550 align:middle line:10%
underneath two miles of water.

00:01:26.550 --> 00:01:28.410 align:middle line:90%
I said, how can that happen?

00:01:28.410 --> 00:01:32.040 align:middle line:84%
And I'd sort of known that
science holds that there

00:01:32.040 --> 00:01:33.940 align:middle line:90%
was never a worldwide flood.

00:01:33.940 --> 00:01:36.210 align:middle line:84%
And so there was a
disparity between the two.

00:01:36.210 --> 00:01:37.890 align:middle line:84%
And I said, well,
I'm a scientist.

00:01:37.890 --> 00:01:39.150 align:middle line:90%
Let's look into it.

00:01:39.150 --> 00:01:40.200 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Not a geologist.

00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:41.366 align:middle line:90%
>>JAYE: I'm not a geologist.

00:01:41.366 --> 00:01:43.300 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: But a
scientist, like this.

00:01:43.300 --> 00:01:44.530 align:middle line:90%
What are we looking at here?

00:01:44.530 --> 00:01:47.520 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: So you can see the
Monterey Peninsula sort of just

00:01:47.520 --> 00:01:49.720 align:middle line:90%
right of center of the image.

00:01:49.720 --> 00:01:52.530 align:middle line:84%
And we can see
what appears to be

00:01:52.530 --> 00:01:54.750 align:middle line:90%
a river system that flows out.

00:01:54.750 --> 00:01:56.050 align:middle line:90%
We can see a meander.

00:01:56.050 --> 00:01:56.850 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: OK.

00:01:56.850 --> 00:01:59.070 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: Just to the
east of Monterey

00:01:59.070 --> 00:02:01.800 align:middle line:84%
is the Salinas Valley,
which was once a lake.

00:02:01.800 --> 00:02:04.990 align:middle line:84%
And that lake drained down
the continental margin,

00:02:04.990 --> 00:02:09.690 align:middle line:84%
which is approximately two miles
high, and created that system.

00:02:09.690 --> 00:02:12.754 align:middle line:84%
That's water that carved
that, at least so I thought

00:02:12.754 --> 00:02:13.920 align:middle line:90%
it was water that carved it.

00:02:13.920 --> 00:02:16.503 align:middle line:84%
And we can see that there is a
system that came from the Santa

00:02:16.503 --> 00:02:22.920 align:middle line:84%
Cruz area, and it merged in
with the river, the main system,

00:02:22.920 --> 00:02:25.340 align:middle line:90%
down to the right.

00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:28.756 align:middle line:10%
And sort of lower from
Monterey is the Big Sur area.

00:02:28.756 --> 00:02:31.380 align:middle line:84%
And we can see all the drainage
is there and how they combined.

00:02:31.380 --> 00:02:32.645 align:middle line:90%
And one of them flowed out.

00:02:32.645 --> 00:02:34.020 align:middle line:84%
Now we can't quite
see it so well

00:02:34.020 --> 00:02:36.030 align:middle line:84%
because in the
abyssal plain, it's

00:02:36.030 --> 00:02:38.010 align:middle line:90%
flat pretty much down there.

00:02:38.010 --> 00:02:39.630 align:middle line:84%
And it's all filled
in with sand,

00:02:39.630 --> 00:02:41.970 align:middle line:84%
but that system also
merged with the main one.

00:02:41.970 --> 00:02:45.820 align:middle line:84%
And we can't see the end of it,
but it flowed over 100 miles.

00:02:45.820 --> 00:02:46.620 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: All right.

00:02:46.620 --> 00:02:48.160 align:middle line:84%
When you looked
at this, Michael,

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:50.100 align:middle line:84%
tell me what the
significance was

00:02:50.100 --> 00:02:53.880 align:middle line:84%
of what you saw that
was so mind boggling

00:02:53.880 --> 00:02:55.820 align:middle line:90%
from what others have seen.

00:02:55.820 --> 00:02:58.900 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: Well, ah,
so this is new data.

00:02:58.900 --> 00:03:00.960 align:middle line:84%
This is the first
time that we humans

00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:02.610 align:middle line:90%
could see into the bathymetry.

00:03:02.610 --> 00:03:07.590 align:middle line:84%
We can see the topography
of submerged landscapes.

00:03:07.590 --> 00:03:09.090 align:middle line:84%
It's the first time
we could see it.

00:03:09.090 --> 00:03:10.560 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So that's what
we were looking at,

00:03:10.560 --> 00:03:11.490 align:middle line:90%
submerged landscapes.

00:03:11.490 --> 00:03:12.450 align:middle line:90%
>>JAYE: So that's new data.

00:03:12.450 --> 00:03:12.780 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: OK.

00:03:12.780 --> 00:03:14.110 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: Those are
submerged landscapes.

00:03:14.110 --> 00:03:15.690 align:middle line:84%
The first time we
could see it was

00:03:15.690 --> 00:03:17.280 align:middle line:90%
when Google published its map.

00:03:17.280 --> 00:03:19.860 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What does
that tell you?

00:03:19.860 --> 00:03:24.810 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: So from a historical,
from a scientific standpoint,

00:03:24.810 --> 00:03:27.000 align:middle line:90%
what we're--

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:28.710 align:middle line:84%
Marcelo Gleiser
has a book called

00:03:28.710 --> 00:03:30.100 align:middle line:90%
"The Island of Knowledge."

00:03:30.100 --> 00:03:32.100 align:middle line:84%
And one of his
chapters is titled

00:03:32.100 --> 00:03:36.090 align:middle line:84%
"The Transformative Power of
a New Observational Tool."

00:03:36.090 --> 00:03:41.680 align:middle line:84%
And what we'll see is that
this event is equivalent.

00:03:41.680 --> 00:03:44.490 align:middle line:84%
It falls into his
classification because the tool

00:03:44.490 --> 00:03:48.600 align:middle line:84%
that he talks about in this
chapter is the telescope.

00:03:48.600 --> 00:03:50.877 align:middle line:84%
And the paradigm that
existed at the time

00:03:50.877 --> 00:03:52.960 align:middle line:84%
was that the Earth was the
center of the universe.

00:03:52.960 --> 00:03:55.140 align:middle line:84%
So this is a new
observational tool,

00:03:55.140 --> 00:03:59.580 align:middle line:84%
the new observational tool that
undid a prevailing paradigm.

00:03:59.580 --> 00:04:04.800 align:middle line:84%
It was a scientific
revolution, was the telescope.

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:06.720 align:middle line:84%
And the telescope
allowed Galileo

00:04:06.720 --> 00:04:09.885 align:middle line:84%
to see that the moons of Jupiter
went around Jupiter, all right.

00:04:09.885 --> 00:04:10.685 align:middle line:90%
It was an anomaly.

00:04:10.685 --> 00:04:11.370 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:04:11.370 --> 00:04:12.828 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: It was an
observation or it

00:04:12.828 --> 00:04:15.210 align:middle line:84%
was a piece of data that
didn't fit into the prevailing

00:04:15.210 --> 00:04:16.010 align:middle line:90%
paradigm.

00:04:16.010 --> 00:04:18.540 align:middle line:84%
Point is is that
the observation,

00:04:18.540 --> 00:04:21.999 align:middle line:84%
the data contradicted
theory that the Earth

00:04:21.999 --> 00:04:23.290 align:middle line:90%
was the center of the universe.

00:04:23.290 --> 00:04:24.832 align:middle line:84%
And so the theory
had to be rejected.

00:04:24.832 --> 00:04:25.631 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: OK.

00:04:25.631 --> 00:04:26.520 align:middle line:90%
>>JAYE: And it was.

00:04:26.520 --> 00:04:30.540 align:middle line:84%
So now here we are 200 years
after geologists decided

00:04:30.540 --> 00:04:32.290 align:middle line:90%
that there was never a flood.

00:04:32.290 --> 00:04:34.020 align:middle line:84%
We'll talk about
that in a moment.

00:04:34.020 --> 00:04:35.640 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Big mistake.

00:04:35.640 --> 00:04:37.890 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: It's a big mistake
in the history of science.

00:04:37.890 --> 00:04:42.000 align:middle line:84%
I'll be borne out in
time with that claim.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:44.595 align:middle line:84%
So 200 years ago,
geologists decided

00:04:44.595 --> 00:04:46.260 align:middle line:90%
that there wasn't a flood.

00:04:46.260 --> 00:04:49.290 align:middle line:84%
And there's been no
contradictory evidence--

00:04:49.290 --> 00:04:52.230 align:middle line:84%
we'll talk about that-- until
the publication of those maps.

00:04:52.230 --> 00:04:55.770 align:middle line:84%
So that's why Google Maps
are the historical equivalent

00:04:55.770 --> 00:04:57.510 align:middle line:90%
of Galileo's telescope.

00:04:57.510 --> 00:05:00.540 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How could the
Bible depict the flood

00:05:00.540 --> 00:05:04.570 align:middle line:84%
and then geologists
refute it 200 years ago?

00:05:04.570 --> 00:05:08.290 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: Well, that's a
fascinating part of the story.

00:05:08.290 --> 00:05:11.850 align:middle line:84%
First of all, flood traditions,
the story of a flood

00:05:11.850 --> 00:05:13.479 align:middle line:90%
is not just in the Bible.

00:05:13.479 --> 00:05:14.520 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It's everywhere.

00:05:14.520 --> 00:05:16.200 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: They're
ubiquitous in cultures

00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:17.060 align:middle line:90%
from around the planet.

00:05:17.060 --> 00:05:17.860 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Correct.

00:05:17.860 --> 00:05:21.570 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: It was a big event,
this contradiction of science

00:05:21.570 --> 00:05:23.580 align:middle line:84%
and the human
narrative tradition.

00:05:23.580 --> 00:05:26.302 align:middle line:84%
So the question then really
is, why do we believe

00:05:26.302 --> 00:05:27.510 align:middle line:90%
that there was never a flood?

00:05:27.510 --> 00:05:31.230 align:middle line:90%
Why does geology hold that?

00:05:31.230 --> 00:05:33.412 align:middle line:84%
This is where I started
digging into geology.

00:05:33.412 --> 00:05:35.370 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Because you
believe there was a flood.

00:05:35.370 --> 00:05:37.890 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: Well, at the time I'm
a scientist, and I was told,

00:05:37.890 --> 00:05:40.110 align:middle line:84%
I believed, I had in
the back of my mind

00:05:40.110 --> 00:05:42.510 align:middle line:90%
that there was never a flood.

00:05:42.510 --> 00:05:43.710 align:middle line:90%
So I wanted to know why.

00:05:43.710 --> 00:05:46.830 align:middle line:84%
Why is it that we believe
that there was never a flood?

00:05:46.830 --> 00:05:49.360 align:middle line:90%
And the story goes like this.

00:05:49.360 --> 00:05:52.440 align:middle line:84%
It's the early
decades of the 1800s.

00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:54.300 align:middle line:84%
And the question before
science-- science

00:05:54.300 --> 00:06:00.060 align:middle line:84%
is just getting formalized as
organized societies, publishing

00:06:00.060 --> 00:06:01.350 align:middle line:90%
materials.

00:06:01.350 --> 00:06:07.080 align:middle line:84%
And at the Geological Society
of London, its chair at the time

00:06:07.080 --> 00:06:09.450 align:middle line:84%
was a gentleman
named Adam Sedgwick.

00:06:09.450 --> 00:06:12.000 align:middle line:84%
And not only was he the
chair of the society,

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:14.229 align:middle line:84%
he was also a
professor at Cambridge.

00:06:14.229 --> 00:06:15.770 align:middle line:84%
And he was also an
ordained minister.

00:06:15.770 --> 00:06:16.590 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Oh, jeez.

00:06:16.590 --> 00:06:18.120 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: In the
Church of England.

00:06:18.120 --> 00:06:21.390 align:middle line:84%
And so Sedgwick set about
Europe with his colleagues,

00:06:21.390 --> 00:06:24.690 align:middle line:84%
and they're looking for
the signs of a flood.

00:06:24.690 --> 00:06:27.420 align:middle line:84%
Now I live on a river, and
we've had a lot of rain

00:06:27.420 --> 00:06:28.400 align:middle line:90%
back in Pennsylvania.

00:06:28.400 --> 00:06:29.075 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:06:29.075 --> 00:06:29.875 align:middle line:90%
Oh, yeah.

00:06:29.875 --> 00:06:32.670 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: And when the rivers
flood, they bring material up,

00:06:32.670 --> 00:06:34.200 align:middle line:90%
and they deposit it.

00:06:34.200 --> 00:06:36.090 align:middle line:84%
And so these geologists
set about Europe

00:06:36.090 --> 00:06:40.110 align:middle line:84%
looking for a common deposit
layer left by the flood.

00:06:40.110 --> 00:06:43.070 align:middle line:90%
And they couldn't find it.

00:06:43.070 --> 00:06:44.720 align:middle line:84%
So because they
couldn't find it--

00:06:44.720 --> 00:06:45.780 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: No flood.

00:06:45.780 --> 00:06:47.905 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: They conclude that
there was never a flood.

00:06:47.905 --> 00:06:50.634 align:middle line:84%
So in his 1831 address
to his society,

00:06:50.634 --> 00:06:51.800 align:middle line:90%
Sedgwick said the following.

00:06:51.800 --> 00:06:53.508 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to quote
him as close as I can.

00:06:53.508 --> 00:06:56.300 align:middle line:84%
He said, "The vast
masses of diluvial gravel

00:06:56.300 --> 00:06:59.270 align:middle line:84%
do not belong to one violent
and transitory period.

00:06:59.270 --> 00:07:00.910 align:middle line:84%
It was the most
unwarranted conclusion.

00:07:00.910 --> 00:07:02.600 align:middle line:84%
We had assumed the
contemporaneity

00:07:02.600 --> 00:07:05.000 align:middle line:84%
of all the superficial
gravels on the earth.

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:09.270 align:middle line:84%
Having been myself a believer
and the best of my power

00:07:09.270 --> 00:07:13.070 align:middle line:84%
a propagator of what I now
regard as a philosophic heresy,

00:07:13.070 --> 00:07:15.820 align:middle line:84%
I think it right that
I read my recantation."

00:07:15.820 --> 00:07:17.780 align:middle line:90%
So he addressed his society.

00:07:17.780 --> 00:07:20.540 align:middle line:84%
Here's a professor, an
ordained minister saying,

00:07:20.540 --> 00:07:21.980 align:middle line:90%
I no longer believe in a flood.

00:07:21.980 --> 00:07:24.270 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Whoa, which was
dramatic at that time,

00:07:24.270 --> 00:07:25.070 align:middle line:90%
wasn't it?

00:07:25.070 --> 00:07:25.870 align:middle line:90%
>>JAYE: It was.

00:07:25.870 --> 00:07:28.640 align:middle line:84%
And it remains
celebrated as the triumph

00:07:28.640 --> 00:07:29.990 align:middle line:90%
of science over religion.

00:07:29.990 --> 00:07:33.380 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Because by
saying that, you're

00:07:33.380 --> 00:07:35.430 align:middle line:84%
saying that the
Bible is inaccurate.

00:07:35.430 --> 00:07:36.230 align:middle line:90%
>>JAYE: Correct.

00:07:36.230 --> 00:07:38.330 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And if it's
wrong about the flood,

00:07:38.330 --> 00:07:40.040 align:middle line:84%
it could be wrong
about everything.

00:07:40.040 --> 00:07:43.790 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: So in a book called
"The Flamingo's Smile,"

00:07:43.790 --> 00:07:47.750 align:middle line:84%
I think it is, the author talks
about Sedgwick and the courage

00:07:47.750 --> 00:07:50.300 align:middle line:84%
that it took for
Sedgwick to make

00:07:50.300 --> 00:07:53.840 align:middle line:84%
this recantation because he
was an ordained minister.

00:07:53.840 --> 00:07:55.550 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Was it
courage or stupidity?

00:07:55.550 --> 00:07:57.792 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: Oh no, it was
courage on his part.

00:07:57.792 --> 00:07:57.950 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It was courage.

00:07:57.950 --> 00:08:00.170 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: I mean, to renounce
his belief in something

00:08:00.170 --> 00:08:01.610 align:middle line:90%
that he professed.

00:08:01.610 --> 00:08:03.540 align:middle line:90%
So that was a big event.

00:08:03.540 --> 00:08:07.160 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So you set out to
prove the flood did occur.

00:08:07.160 --> 00:08:11.510 align:middle line:90%
>>JAYE: Well, so-- not yet.

00:08:11.510 --> 00:08:14.150 align:middle line:84%
I guess we'll get
right to it then.

00:08:14.150 --> 00:08:17.420 align:middle line:84%
What is the problem with
what Sedgwick concluded?

00:08:17.420 --> 00:08:20.840 align:middle line:84%
So I looked at these maps,
and they led me to realize--

00:08:20.840 --> 00:08:25.520 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you can't get
carved water or these rivers

00:08:25.520 --> 00:08:26.390 align:middle line:90%
submerged.

00:08:26.390 --> 00:08:27.830 align:middle line:84%
The density of
water is too much.

00:08:27.830 --> 00:08:29.390 align:middle line:84%
You can't have
concentrated flows.

00:08:29.390 --> 00:08:32.570 align:middle line:84%
Yes, there's large
scale flows, but not

00:08:32.570 --> 00:08:36.140 align:middle line:84%
concentrated flows going out
hundreds of miles subsurface.

00:08:36.140 --> 00:08:38.780 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And it's not just
Monterey, it's everywhere.

00:08:38.780 --> 00:08:40.289 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: They're
around the planet.

00:08:40.289 --> 00:08:42.785 align:middle line:90%
So I set out to find out why.

00:08:42.785 --> 00:08:45.210 align:middle line:84%
Why is it that we believe
that there was never a flood?

00:08:45.210 --> 00:08:47.090 align:middle line:84%
And so as I've
described, Sedgwick

00:08:47.090 --> 00:08:49.506 align:middle line:84%
is the person who is
responsible for the belief.

00:08:49.506 --> 00:08:51.380 align:middle line:84%
And it was celebrated
as a triumph of science

00:08:51.380 --> 00:08:53.930 align:middle line:84%
over religion, and it
remains so to this day.

