through the Oort Cloud.

00:25:45.880 --> 00:25:47.625 align:middle line:84%
So here now we have
two massive stars.

00:25:47.625 --> 00:25:49.000 align:middle line:84%
They pass through
the Oort Cloud.

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:51.070 align:middle line:90%
They likely perturb this object.

00:25:51.070 --> 00:25:54.820 align:middle line:84%
So here this object has got
100-mile diameter center

00:25:54.820 --> 00:25:57.550 align:middle line:84%
solid core, and it's
surrounded on the outside

00:25:57.550 --> 00:26:01.441 align:middle line:84%
by ice chunks that
came in very slowly.

00:26:01.441 --> 00:26:02.440 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Building on it.

00:26:02.440 --> 00:26:03.856 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: Another
thing about comets

00:26:03.856 --> 00:26:06.080 align:middle line:84%
is the United States
sent a probe into a comet

00:26:06.080 --> 00:26:06.880 align:middle line:90%
not too long ago.

00:26:06.880 --> 00:26:09.460 align:middle line:84%
It was called Deep
Impact Mission.

00:26:09.460 --> 00:26:11.710 align:middle line:84%
Michael A'Hearn from
University of Maryland

00:26:11.710 --> 00:26:13.510 align:middle line:90%
was the project chair.

00:26:13.510 --> 00:26:16.120 align:middle line:84%
There were two objects
that we sent out.

00:26:16.120 --> 00:26:17.770 align:middle line:84%
One was going to
be a probe that's

00:26:17.770 --> 00:26:19.037 align:middle line:90%
going to go into the comet.

00:26:19.037 --> 00:26:20.620 align:middle line:84%
And the other one's
going to observe--

00:26:20.620 --> 00:26:22.040 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: From above.

00:26:22.040 --> 00:26:23.699 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: Outside and
see what happens.

00:26:23.699 --> 00:26:25.240 align:middle line:84%
And one of the things
that they found

00:26:25.240 --> 00:26:29.560 align:middle line:84%
is that comets are mostly
open space, 75% open space.

00:26:29.560 --> 00:26:33.640 align:middle line:84%
Of the mass of a comet,
2/3 of the mass is ice.

00:26:33.640 --> 00:26:37.840 align:middle line:84%
And the other third of the mass
would be minerals and whatnot.

00:26:37.840 --> 00:26:39.160 align:middle line:90%
That's important.

00:26:39.160 --> 00:26:42.460 align:middle line:84%
So the object-- so
we've got this sphere.

00:26:42.460 --> 00:26:45.800 align:middle line:84%
It's going to be 1,500-mile-wide
sphere, diameter sphere.

00:26:45.800 --> 00:26:46.600 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Huge.

00:26:46.600 --> 00:26:49.960 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: It's a big
object, but it's porous.

00:26:49.960 --> 00:26:52.810 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That's a sixth
of the size of the planet.

00:26:52.810 --> 00:26:54.250 align:middle line:90%
>>JAYE: It's a big object.

00:26:54.250 --> 00:26:57.490 align:middle line:84%
And it gets perturbed by
this binary star system,

00:26:57.490 --> 00:26:59.120 align:middle line:90%
and it gets some velocity.

00:26:59.120 --> 00:27:00.245 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And here it comes.

00:27:00.245 --> 00:27:05.750 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: And 57,000 years later,
it comes and it hits the Earth.

00:27:05.750 --> 00:27:06.780 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sheesh.

00:27:06.780 --> 00:27:08.950 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: If we could put up that
one image of what it looked

00:27:08.950 --> 00:27:09.070 align:middle line:90%
like.

00:27:09.070 --> 00:27:10.187 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: All right,
let's take a look.

00:27:10.187 --> 00:27:12.280 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: So it's the
schematic-- there it is.

00:27:12.280 --> 00:27:17.970 align:middle line:84%
So it has an ice outer layer,
and it's got this solid core.

00:27:17.970 --> 00:27:19.219 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And how big is that?

00:27:19.219 --> 00:27:20.760 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: Well, in
our case, it's going

00:27:20.760 --> 00:27:22.580 align:middle line:84%
to be 1,500 miles in
diameter, roughly.

00:27:22.580 --> 00:27:23.380 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Whoa.

00:27:23.380 --> 00:27:28.320 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: And it's-- but it's
really key, its composition.

00:27:28.320 --> 00:27:29.400 align:middle line:90%
It's not solidly packed.

00:27:29.400 --> 00:27:31.900 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It would have destroyed
the planet if it was solid.

00:27:31.900 --> 00:27:33.330 align:middle line:90%
>>JAYE: No, no, no, no.

00:27:33.330 --> 00:27:34.920 align:middle line:90%
It's loosely packed.

00:27:34.920 --> 00:27:36.420 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I mean,
had it been solid--

00:27:36.420 --> 00:27:36.690 align:middle line:90%
>>JAYE: That's right.

00:27:36.690 --> 00:27:38.055 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: --it would've
annihilated us.

00:27:38.055 --> 00:27:39.630 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: It would have
been a significant event.

00:27:39.630 --> 00:27:39.990 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yes.

00:27:39.990 --> 00:27:41.698 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: Well, it was
a significant event.

00:27:41.698 --> 00:27:44.670 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So it breaks up
and melts as it gets closer?

00:27:44.670 --> 00:27:47.850 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: Well, so the comets
that we observe-- in fact, I

00:27:47.850 --> 00:27:49.350 align:middle line:84%
think all the comets
that we observe

00:27:49.350 --> 00:27:51.600 align:middle line:84%
are fragments of the object
that end up hitting the Earth.

00:27:51.600 --> 00:27:52.808 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's a good point.

00:27:52.808 --> 00:27:54.270 align:middle line:90%
>>JAYE: So I call this object--

00:27:54.270 --> 00:27:56.910 align:middle line:84%
I don't want to
intrude upon cosmology,

00:27:56.910 --> 00:28:01.540 align:middle line:84%
so I simply call it the
impacting object, the IO.

00:28:01.540 --> 00:28:04.080 align:middle line:84%
And so the question
is, what's it

00:28:04.080 --> 00:28:05.940 align:middle line:84%
going to be like when
it hits the Earth?

00:28:05.940 --> 00:28:06.740 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sure.

00:28:06.740 --> 00:28:08.940 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: It's less
strong than a snowbank.

00:28:08.940 --> 00:28:11.970 align:middle line:84%
So when this thing hits,
it's going to be a thud.

00:28:11.970 --> 00:28:16.680 align:middle line:84%
It's not going to be a planet
killing event, but that center

00:28:16.680 --> 00:28:18.720 align:middle line:84%
core, what's the center
core going to do?

00:28:18.720 --> 00:28:20.190 align:middle line:84%
When that thing
hits, it's solid.

00:28:20.190 --> 00:28:22.113 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That iron core
you're talking about.

00:28:22.113 --> 00:28:22.913 align:middle line:90%
>>JAYE: Yeah.

00:28:22.913 --> 00:28:24.690 align:middle line:84%
So when it hits,
it's going to gouge.

00:28:24.690 --> 00:28:26.280 align:middle line:84%
So if we could see
the next image,

00:28:26.280 --> 00:28:27.810 align:middle line:84%
this is going to
be the impact site.

00:28:27.810 --> 00:28:28.872 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: All right.

00:28:28.872 --> 00:28:29.830 align:middle line:90%
>>JAYE: So there it is.

00:28:29.830 --> 00:28:32.970 align:middle line:84%
I have superimposed
on it a diameter.

00:28:32.970 --> 00:28:35.400 align:middle line:90%
That diameter is 1,500 miles.

00:28:35.400 --> 00:28:39.362 align:middle line:84%
We can see the central scrape
that was carved by the--

00:28:39.362 --> 00:28:41.070 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That's where
you believe it hit?

00:28:41.070 --> 00:28:42.180 align:middle line:90%
>>JAYE: Yes.

00:28:42.180 --> 00:28:44.020 align:middle line:90%
That's South Africa.

00:28:44.020 --> 00:28:46.090 align:middle line:90%
It's southeast of South Africa.

00:28:46.090 --> 00:28:47.160 align:middle line:90%
It's north of Antarctica.

00:28:47.160 --> 00:28:50.970 align:middle line:90%
And it is south of Madagascar.

00:28:50.970 --> 00:28:52.440 align:middle line:90%
So it's in the Southern Ocean.

00:28:52.440 --> 00:28:55.590 align:middle line:84%
We can see the arc
from the impact.

00:28:55.590 --> 00:28:56.460 align:middle line:90%
It gives us an idea.

00:28:56.460 --> 00:28:57.330 align:middle line:90%
It's not circular.

00:28:57.330 --> 00:28:59.540 align:middle line:84%
So that gives us an
idea that it approached

00:28:59.540 --> 00:29:01.860 align:middle line:90%
at a somewhat shallow angle.

00:29:01.860 --> 00:29:03.145 align:middle line:90%
We have a gap in the center.

00:29:03.145 --> 00:29:07.500 align:middle line:84%
In fact, we could put the
next slide up that shows--

00:29:07.500 --> 00:29:09.600 align:middle line:84%
will show the impact
site as well as

00:29:09.600 --> 00:29:11.220 align:middle line:90%
an overlay, a magnetic anomaly.

00:29:11.220 --> 00:29:12.250 align:middle line:90%
There we go.

00:29:12.250 --> 00:29:14.100 align:middle line:84%
So we have the exact
same image on top.

00:29:14.100 --> 00:29:17.340 align:middle line:84%
And from the exact same
Google Earth perspective,

00:29:17.340 --> 00:29:20.400 align:middle line:84%
we have shown below a
magnetic anomaly overlay that

00:29:20.400 --> 00:29:24.060 align:middle line:84%
shows that there were materials
strewn by the impact velocity

00:29:24.060 --> 00:29:26.322 align:middle line:90%
through the crescent gap.

00:29:26.322 --> 00:29:28.530 align:middle line:84%
So the fact that we see
there's a crescent gap almost

00:29:28.530 --> 00:29:31.140 align:middle line:84%
implies that the object,
because it was so fragile when

00:29:31.140 --> 00:29:33.230 align:middle line:84%
it started interacting
with Earth's atmosphere,

00:29:33.230 --> 00:29:35.440 align:middle line:90%
it split in two.

00:29:35.440 --> 00:29:36.330 align:middle line:90%
And so it hits.

00:29:36.330 --> 00:29:41.040 align:middle line:84%
It creates these crescents,
these half crescents.

00:29:41.040 --> 00:29:44.970 align:middle line:84%
And eventually when
this ice melts,

00:29:44.970 --> 00:29:46.530 align:middle line:84%
well, we get a couple
deposit mounds.

00:29:46.530 --> 00:29:48.363 align:middle line:84%
In fact, you can see
there's a raised region

00:29:48.363 --> 00:29:51.240 align:middle line:84%
just on the left
side of the diameter.

00:29:51.240 --> 00:29:53.790 align:middle line:84%
That's a deposit mound from
the minerals and whatnot

00:29:53.790 --> 00:29:55.230 align:middle line:90%
that the thing brought.

00:29:55.230 --> 00:29:58.560 align:middle line:84%
Minerals were strewn through
the gap about 1,000 miles due

00:29:58.560 --> 00:30:00.121 align:middle line:90%
to impact velocities.

00:30:00.121 --> 00:30:01.870 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Would you
have heard it from here

00:30:01.870 --> 00:30:03.344 align:middle line:90%
if it had hit this impact?

00:30:03.344 --> 00:30:05.010 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: You probably
would have felt it.

00:30:05.010 --> 00:30:07.210 align:middle line:90%
There probably was a worldwide--

00:30:07.210 --> 00:30:08.010 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Jarring.

00:30:08.010 --> 00:30:08.190 align:middle line:90%
>>JAYE: Right.

00:30:08.190 --> 00:30:10.380 align:middle line:84%
But imagine what this thing
looked like as it was coming.

00:30:10.380 --> 00:30:11.260 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Coming in.

00:30:11.260 --> 00:30:13.176 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: Imagine what it
looked like coming in.

00:30:13.176 --> 00:30:14.670 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It took
up the whole sky.

00:30:14.670 --> 00:30:18.780 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: So we can see comets
from millions of miles away,

00:30:18.780 --> 00:30:21.250 align:middle line:84%
and they're but fractions
of the size of this thing.

00:30:21.250 --> 00:30:24.180 align:middle line:84%
I mean, Halley's-- we
could fit roughly a million

00:30:24.180 --> 00:30:25.410 align:middle line:90%
Halley's Comets into--

00:30:25.410 --> 00:30:27.240 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: How did it get so big?

00:30:27.240 --> 00:30:28.290 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: Well, it was
in the Oort Cloud.

00:30:28.290 --> 00:30:29.690 align:middle line:84%
It sat there for
bazillions of years.

00:30:29.690 --> 00:30:30.697 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Just building
up, building up.

00:30:30.697 --> 00:30:32.821 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: Collecting up that
ice and little minerals.

00:30:32.821 --> 00:30:34.680 align:middle line:90%
And it got displaced.

00:30:34.680 --> 00:30:35.490 align:middle line:90%
And here it is.

00:30:35.490 --> 00:30:38.420 align:middle line:84%
Big sky, little bullet,
it hits the Earth

00:30:38.420 --> 00:30:41.220 align:middle line:90%
roughly 13,000 years ago.

00:30:41.220 --> 00:30:44.400 align:middle line:84%
And the ice that
it brings is going

00:30:44.400 --> 00:30:46.894 align:middle line:90%
to melt and flood the planet.

00:30:46.894 --> 00:30:49.249 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Ah, and the
oceans and everything else.

00:30:49.249 --> 00:30:51.540 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: And so because we
know how comets are composed,

00:30:51.540 --> 00:30:52.831 align:middle line:90%
we can do a little bit of math.

00:30:52.831 --> 00:30:55.650 align:middle line:84%
We can find the volume of the
sphere of that 1,500-mile-wide

00:30:55.650 --> 00:30:56.450 align:middle line:90%
sphere.

00:30:56.450 --> 00:30:58.170 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Because it was
all frozen water basically,

00:30:58.170 --> 00:30:58.970 align:middle line:90%
wasn't it?

00:30:58.970 --> 00:31:02.520 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: Well, one sixth of the
volume would have been ice.

00:31:02.520 --> 00:31:04.530 align:middle line:90%
We can convert the ice to water.

00:31:04.530 --> 00:31:07.230 align:middle line:84%
And then we can take
that volume and divide it

00:31:07.230 --> 00:31:11.382 align:middle line:84%
by the Earth's known
surface area of the oceans.

00:31:11.382 --> 00:31:13.340 align:middle line:84%
And take the volume,
divide it by surface area,

00:31:13.340 --> 00:31:14.340 align:middle line:90%
you get a height.

00:31:14.340 --> 00:31:16.950 align:middle line:84%
And that height is just a
little bit over two miles.

00:31:16.950 --> 00:31:19.660 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Two miles of
water basically came in?

00:31:19.660 --> 00:31:21.660 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: This object
delivered two miles of water

00:31:21.660 --> 00:31:22.930 align:middle line:90%
13,000 years ago.

00:31:22.930 --> 00:31:23.730 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Sheesh.

00:31:23.730 --> 00:31:25.870 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: And it
flooded the planet.

00:31:25.870 --> 00:31:29.160 align:middle line:84%
Now we humans, we're
not from up here.

00:31:29.160 --> 00:31:32.010 align:middle line:84%
We are not from presently
exposed landscapes.

00:31:32.010 --> 00:31:36.210 align:middle line:84%
We are from landscapes that are
now under two miles of water.

00:31:36.210 --> 00:31:38.970 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Could Atlantis have
been one of these areas?

00:31:38.970 --> 00:31:40.750 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: I gave a talk
a couple years ago

00:31:40.750 --> 00:31:42.480 align:middle line:84%
at the Explorers Club
called "Resolving

00:31:42.480 --> 00:31:44.130 align:middle line:90%
the Problem of Atlantis."

00:31:44.130 --> 00:31:46.220 align:middle line:84%
Yes, Atlantis existed,
so did Lemuria,

00:31:46.220 --> 00:31:52.110 align:middle line:84%
two famous civilizations
that are discounted as myth.

00:31:52.110 --> 00:31:56.340 align:middle line:84%
They're the ramblings
of rubes, ancients.

00:31:56.340 --> 00:32:00.970 align:middle line:84%
They're all discounted because
of this error in geology.

00:32:00.970 --> 00:32:02.470 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: This is amazing.

00:32:02.470 --> 00:32:03.270 align:middle line:90%
Great work.

00:32:03.270 --> 00:32:05.436 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: Maybe to have a
little further more evidence

00:32:05.436 --> 00:32:08.140 align:middle line:90%
of the flood.

00:32:08.140 --> 00:32:10.590 align:middle line:90%
So the next image, I think, is--

00:32:10.590 --> 00:32:11.700 align:middle line:90%
oh, yes.

00:32:11.700 --> 00:32:15.249 align:middle line:84%
This is from a cave in
Fouriesburg, South Africa.

00:32:15.249 --> 00:32:16.540 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: From inside of a cave?

00:32:16.540 --> 00:32:18.123 align:middle line:10%
>>JAYE: This is from
inside of a cave.

00:32:18.123 --> 00:32:20.510 align:middle line:84%
So we humans were flushed
out of the landscapes where

00:32:20.510 --> 00:32:25.410 align:middle line:84%
we evolved, where we were living
for tens of millions of years

00:32:25.410 --> 00:32:26.390 align:middle line:90%
probably.

00:32:26.390 --> 00:32:30.350 align:middle line:84%
And survivors, their
first place to go

00:32:30.350 --> 00:32:33.560 align:middle line:84%
was a cave because the
landscapes are colder.

00:32:33.560 --> 00:32:36.890 align:middle line:84%
Everything is different
to the survivors.

00:32:36.890 --> 00:32:37.700 align:middle line:90%
They needed warmth.

00:32:37.700 --> 00:32:38.960 align:middle line:90%
They needed shelter.

00:32:38.960 --> 00:32:40.770 align:middle line:90%
Immediate place to go is a cave.

00:32:40.770 --> 00:32:42.500 align:middle line:84%
So this is in
Fouriesburg, South Africa.

00:32:42.500 --> 00:32:45.440 align:middle line:84%
And one of the
survivors sketched

00:32:45.440 --> 00:32:51.380 align:middle line:84%
on this cave what I
believe is his recounting

00:32:51.380 --> 00:32:54.270 align:middle line:84%
of how the impacting
object looked to him.

00:32:54.270 --> 00:32:56.927 align:middle line:84%
First of all, it's
drawn in light color.

00:32:56.927 --> 00:32:58.510 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Is it that
line we're seeing?

00:32:58.510 --> 00:32:59.310 align:middle line:90%
>>JAYE: Yeah.

00:32:59.310 --> 00:33:02.090 align:middle line:10%
So coming from right to left,
notice the shallow angle.

00:33:02.090 --> 00:33:05.120 align:middle line:10%
This impacting object came
in at a fairly shallow angle,

00:33:05.120 --> 00:33:07.750 align:middle line:10%
which is why we don't see
a full circular crescent.

00:33:07.750 --> 00:33:10.940 align:middle line:10%
We see a semicircle crescent.

00:33:10.940 --> 00:33:13.100 align:middle line:90%
Notice that it bifurcates.

00:33:13.100 --> 00:33:15.740 align:middle line:84%
So this individual who
is in South Africa,

00:33:15.740 --> 00:33:18.110 align:middle line:84%
to this individual
the impacting object

00:33:18.110 --> 00:33:22.010 align:middle line:84%
would have come from his right,
or his or her right to left.

00:33:22.010 --> 00:33:23.700 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Was this
a witness to this?

00:33:23.700 --> 00:33:24.500 align:middle line:90%
>>JAYE: Yes.

00:33:24.500 --> 00:33:25.890 align:middle line:90%
This is an eyewitness account.

00:33:25.890 --> 00:33:26.690 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Jeez.

00:33:26.690 --> 00:33:28.606 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: There are lots
of eyewitness accounts.

00:33:28.606 --> 00:33:33.350 align:middle line:84%
The Chinese New Year dragon,
this serpent above the clouds.

00:33:33.350 --> 00:33:34.700 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Was this object.

00:33:34.700 --> 00:33:37.210 align:middle line:84%
>>JAYE: With water
emanating from its mouth.

00:33:37.210 --> 00:33:39.350 align:middle line:84%
That is celebrated
every so many years.

00:33:39.350 --> 00:33:43.580 align:middle line:84%
That is a memorialization
of the impacting object

00:33:43.580 --> 00:33:44.480 align:middle line:90%
as it appeared.

00:33:44.480 --> 00:33:46.580 align:middle line:84%
Water emanating from
a dragon's mouth?

00:33:46.580 --> 00:33:48.035 align:middle line:90%
Isn't that interesting.

00:33:48.035 --> 00:33:53.720 align:middle line:84%
And of course, survivors have
maintained this event, even

00:33:53.720 --> 00:33:55.135 align:middle line:90%
though it's 13,000 years ago.

